## Why This Is Asked
Tests basic concurrent data structure design and practical use of atomics and memory ordering in a beginner-friendly but realistic setting.

## Key Concepts
- MPSC synchronization using a shared tail and a local consumer head
- Atomic fetch_add for slot reservation
- Memory ordering: release on enqueue, acquire on dequeue
- Correct wrap-around handling in a fixed-size buffer

## Code Example
```javascript
// Pseudo-C code (C11 atomics style)
#define N (1<<12)
typedef struct { uint64_t data; uint64_t seq; } slot_t;
slot_t buf[N];
atomic_uintptr_t tail = 0; // producer index
size_t head = 0; // consumer index

bool enqueue(uint64_t v){
  size_t t = atomic_fetch_add_explicit(&tail, 1, memory_order_relaxed);
  if (t >= N) return false;
  buf[t].data = v;
  atomic_thread_fence(memory_order_release);
  buf[t].seq = t; // simple wrap-safe signal
  return true;
}

bool dequeue(uint64_t* out){
  if (head >= atomic_load_explicit(&tail, memory_order_acquire)) return false;
  *out = buf[head].data;
  head++;
  return true;
}
```

## Follow-up Questions
- How would you extend this to detect and recover from corrupted data?
- How would you benchmark throughput under 1000 producers vs 1 consumer?

## Why This Is Asked
Tests fundamentals of memory allocators, pointer arithmetic, alignment, and simple free-list management in a low-level setting. It also checks the ability to reason about initialization and fragmentation.

## Key Concepts
- Fixed-size allocator
- Free-list embedded pointers
- Heap initialization
- O(1) allocation/deallocation
- Fragmentation considerations with fixed-size pools

## Code Example
```c
#include <stdint.h>
#include <stddef.h>

#define HEAP_SIZE (64*1024)
#define BLOCK_SIZE 32
#define BLOCKS (HEAP_SIZE / BLOCK_SIZE)

static uint8_t heap[HEAP_SIZE];
static uint32_t free_head;

void init_heap(){
  free_head = 0;
  for(size_t i=0;i<BLOCKS;++i){
    uint32_t next = (i==BLOCKS-1) ? UINT32_MAX : (i+1);
    *((uint32_t*)(heap + i*BLOCK_SIZE)) = next;
  }
}

void* alloc_block(){
  if(free_head==UINT32_MAX) return NULL;
  uint32_t off = free_head;
  free_head = *((uint32_t*)(heap + off*BLOCK_SIZE));
  return (void*)(heap + off*BLOCK_SIZE);
}

void free_block(void* p){
  size_t off = ((uint8_t*)p - heap) / BLOCK_SIZE;
  *((uint32_t*)(heap + off*BLOCK_SIZE)) = free_head;
  free_head = off;
}
```

